Deep Learning for Scandal Prediction

Environment setup

First we have to set up the environment, by loading the necessary libraries, and defining some helper functions to

  • read in the locally stored website source code files

  • strip the of unnecessary code and html script

  • convert unicode character codes to characters (e.g. U+00E4 should be displayed as the German letter ä), and

  • convert the collection of read-in documents into a Quanteda Corpus object, for easy preprocessing of the text data.

# Define helper functions to read in raw source code, strip away html code, turn into corpus object
unescape_html <- function(str){
  xml2::xml_text(xml2::read_html(paste0("<x>", str, "</x>")))
}

read_in_reports <- function(server_path) {
  company_reports <- readtext(server_path,
                              docvarsfrom = "filenames",
                              docvarnames = c("company", "year","index"),
                              dvsep = "_",
                              encoding = "UTF-8",
                              verbosity = 0)
  company_reports_clean <- company_reports
  company_reports_clean$text <- gsub(".*<!-- Publication  -->","",company_reports_clean$text)
  company_reports_clean$text <- gsub("<!-- Result Pager Bottom  -->.*","",company_reports_clean$text)
  company_reports_clean$text <- gsub('<table class="std_table".*?</table>', '', company_reports_clean$text)
  company_reports_clean$text <- gsub('</p>', ' Abstzpltzhltr ', company_reports_clean$text)
  company_reports_clean$text <- gsub('<h', ' Abstzpltzhltr -header_start- <', company_reports_clean$text)
  company_reports_clean$text <- gsub('</h', ' -header_end- <', company_reports_clean$text)
  company_reports_clean$text <- gsub('<.*?>', '', company_reports_clean$text)
  company_reports_clean$text <- str_squish(company_reports_clean$text)
  company_reports_clean$text <- gsub('Abstzpltzhltr', '\n', company_reports_clean$text)
  company_reports_clean$text <- sapply(company_reports_clean$text, function(x) unescape_html(x))
  reports_corpus <- corpus(company_reports_clean)
  return(reports_corpus)
}

print('setup complete')

Extraction of paragraphs that report on ESG matters

Since the full corporate reports are extremely long, and contain a lot of reporting on matters of strategy, finances, etc. with no direct connection to ESG topics, we want to filter to only retain paragraphs that mention ESG topics.

To this end, we first have to define a helper function segment_and_extract(corpus,keywords,output) that, given a set of keywords (for ESG topics) and a desired output style, strip the full reports in the full_reports_corpus corpus object to only paragraphs featuring the keywords.

Parameters:

  • corpus: A Quanteda corpus object that contains the full reports to be cut down

  • keywords: A list of strings, which are to be searched in the paragraphs. When there’s a match to one or more keywords within a paragraph, that paragraph is retained.

  • output: A string indicating the desired output format. Either “corpus_segmented”, which returns a version of the corpus object with texts broken down into paragraphs, without filtering on keywords, or “window_segmented”, which returns a corpus object of only those paragraphs that contain one or more keywords, or “window_merged”, which returns a corpus object of the paragraphs that contain one or more keywords, merged back together into a single cell for each report.

# following function can either extract the full, but segtmented corpus, 
# or only segments with ESG keywords, 
# or segments with ESG keywords merged together (i.e. one cell per company-year)

segment_and_extract <- function(corpus,keywords,output) {
  reports_corpus_seg <- corpus_segment(corpus, pattern = '\n', valuetype = "glob", 
                                       pattern_position = "before", use_docvars = TRUE)
  reports_corpus_seg$ntoken <- ntoken(reports_corpus_seg)
  reports_corpus_seg <- corpus_subset(reports_corpus_seg, ntoken > 0)
  reports_corpus_seg$filter <- str_detect(reports_corpus_seg,
                                          regex(paste(keywords, collapse = "|"),ignore_case = TRUE))
  if (output == "corpus_segmented") {
    return(reports_corpus_seg)
  } else {
    reports_corpus_seg_trim <- corpus_subset(reports_corpus_seg, filter == TRUE)
    reports_corpus_seg$firmyear <- paste0(reports_corpus_seg$company,reports_corpus_seg$year)
    reports_corpus_seg_trim$firmyear <- paste0(reports_corpus_seg_trim$company,reports_corpus_seg_trim$year)
    if (output == "window_segmented") {
      return(reports_corpus_seg_trim)
    } else {
      reports_corpus_window <- corpus_group(reports_corpus_seg_trim, groups = firmyear,concatenator = " ")
      if (output == "window_merged") {
        return(reports_corpus_window)
      } else stop("invalid output setting")
    }
  }
}

Next, we have to define a list of keywords with which we want to filter the full report texts. Here, these are broken down into keywords related to the social and environmental dimensions of ESG, and the governance dimension of ESG (since the governance (G) dimension is economically motivated, one may choose to only look at the social responsibility-motivated E and S dimensions).

# keywords zur Identifikation von Governance-relevanten Textstellen

                         "Führungssystem","Governance","Kodex","Aufsichtsr","board",
                         "Vorstand","Vorständ","Ausschuss","Komitee","comittee","Committee")

keywords <- c(keywords_csr,keywords_governance)

Now, we can run the segment_and_extract() helper function with the keywords we defined. Afterwards, we just need to drop a handful reports that were filed for broken-up fiscal years, and whose content can’t be clearly linked with the corresponding scandals data points.

Note: Since we want to use recurrent neural networks when training a classification model, the input text sequences cannot be too long. There we choose the “window_segmented” output style, aiming to train the neural network on individual paragraphs taken from the reports.

reports_corpus_seg_trim <- segment_and_extract(full_reports_corpus,keywords = keywords,output = "window_segmented")

reports_corpus_seg_trim <- convert(reports_corpus_seg_trim, to = "data.frame")

  filter(!(year %in% c("2013a","2013b","2016a","2016b","2017a","2017b")))

Reading and preprocessing the target variable

First, we have to read in the Excel-Spreadsheet containing the data about companies’ ‘controversy score’, i.e. a measure of whether they are involved in ongoing media scandals over ESG topics. To read in the spreadsheet, we do:

As part of cleaning the scandals data, we have to drop duplicate rows, which can be identified by their identical combination of company and year:

eikon_data$firmyear <- paste0(eikon_data$datastream_id,eikon_data$year)
eikon_data <- distinct(eikon_data, firmyear,.keep_all = TRUE)

To turn the variable ‘ESG Controversies Score’ into our target, we have to first recode it to a binary indicator of whether or not a company is in a given year involved in a scandal. The ‘ESG Controversies Score’ x is…

  • x = 100 if a company is scandal-free in a given year,

  • 0 ≤ x < 100 if a company is involved in a scandal in a given year (with lower values indicating greater severity)

  • x = ‘NA’ if a company was not covered by Refinitv ESG analysts.

Accordingly, we mutate the ‘ESG Controversies Score’ into a new variable ‘controversy’, that is FALSE when a company was scandal-free, TRUE when a company was involved in a scandal, and NA if a company was not covered and the data is thus missing.

eikon_data$controversy <- NA
eikon_data$controversy[!(eikon_data$`ESG Controversies Score` == "NA")] <- TRUE
eikon_data$controversy[eikon_data$`ESG Controversies Score` == "100"] <- FALSE

# Optional: retain controversy_score as optional target for regression modeling
eikon_data <- eikon_data %>%
  rename(controversy_score = `ESG Controversies Score`)
eikon_data <- eikon_data %>%
  mutate(controversy_score = na_if(controversy_score, "NA"))
eikon_data$controversy_score <- as.numeric(eikon_data$controversy_score)

Secondly, as our aim is the prediction of future scandals from companies’ current reporting, we have to generate a variable that indicates whether a company experienced a scandal in the two following years:

contro_t1 <- eikon_data %>%
  select(datastream_id,year,controversy_score,controversy)
contro_t1 <- contro_t1 %>%
  mutate(year = year - 1)
contro_t1 <- contro_t1 %>%
  rename(controversy_score_t1 = controversy_score,
         controversy_t1 = controversy)
contro_t2 <- eikon_data %>%
  select(datastream_id,year,controversy_score,controversy)
contro_t2 <- contro_t2 %>%
  mutate(year = year - 2)
contro_t2 <- contro_t2 %>%
  rename(controversy_score_t2 = controversy_score,
         controversy_t2 = controversy)

eikon_data <- left_join(eikon_data,contro_t1,by = c("datastream_id", "year"))
eikon_data <- left_join(eikon_data,contro_t2,by = c("datastream_id", "year"))
eikon_data <- eikon_data %>%
  mutate(future_controversy = (controversy_t1 | controversy_t2))

rm(contro_t1,contro_t2)

We end up with our target variable future_controversy, which is TRUE if a company experienced a scandal in either of the following two years, and FALSE if it remained scandal-free over the same period.

Deep Learning with Keras

Set up Keras

In order to use Keras in R, we need to a) load the necessary libraries, and b) ‘reticulate’, i.e. tie a version of Python into the R session.

library(caret)
library(keras)
library(tensorflow)
library(reticulate)
use_condaenv(condaenv = "TensorFlow", conda = "auto", required = NULL)
set_random_seed(32)

Build feature tensor

We first tidy up our data a bit, by dropping missing values on the target, dropping text sequences shorter than 10 words (likely headings or single-sentence paragraphs), and keeping only columns we will use in model training.

raw_data <- TTT_analysis_corpus %>%
  filter(!(is.na(future_controversy))) %>%
  filter(ntoken > 10) %>%
  select(doc_id,company.x,year,text,future_controversy,ntoken)

In order to be able to validate the neural networks that we train, we will need to perform a train-test split on the data. We use the most recent 3 years as the validation data, because our aim is to predict future controversies based on past data, and because we don’t want to risk data leakage (by training a model on data from all periods including the latest, and then using it to ‘predict’ scandals in earlier periods). The actual train-test split is performed a bit further below, but we first have to shuffle the data in the train and test sets separately, to avoid order effects on the training. We implement this like:

raw_train <- raw_data %>%
  filter(year < 2019)
raw_train <- raw_train[sample(1:nrow(raw_train)), ]

end_of_train <- nrow(raw_train)
#to index the training set: texts[1:end_of_train]

raw_test <- raw_data %>%
  filter(year>2018)
raw_test <- raw_test[sample(1:nrow(raw_test)), ]

end_of_test <- nrow(raw_train) + nrow(raw_test)

Next, we can tokenize the text, and turn it into sequences. While doing so, we have to decide how large our vocabulary should be (max_words) and to which maximum length we want to trim the sequences (maxlen).

maxlen <- 300 # 99% of text sequences are smaller than this.
max_words <- 50000 #this is close to the total vocabulary size when dropping infrequent words (appearing less than 10 times in the corpus), and practicable, as a larger vocabulary could easily overload our computational resources.

texts <- c(raw_train$text,raw_test$text)
tokenizer <- text_tokenizer(num_words = max_words) %>%
  fit_text_tokenizer(texts)
sequences <- texts_to_sequences(tokenizer, texts)
word_index = tokenizer$word_index
cat(length(word_index), "unique tokens found.\n")
## 186325 unique tokens found.
data <- pad_sequences(sequences, maxlen = maxlen)

With some final reformating, and by re-instating the train-test-split on the now tokenized data, we arrive at the 2D feature tensor (containing the tokenized text sequences) necessary as input to the neural network, and a target array containing the future_controversy label.

labels <- as.numeric(c(raw_train$future_controversy,raw_test$future_controversy))

Word embeddings

One of the simplest deep learning models we can build is one that utilizes word embeddings to encode patterns among the words in the text (e.g. semantic similarity), and then feeds these vectorized representations to some dense network layers that learn how these relate to the target (scandal occurrence).

#simple embeddings + multilayer perceptron
set_random_seed(32)

model1 <- keras_model_sequential() %>%
  layer_embedding(input_dim = max_words, output_dim = 32,
                  input_length = maxlen) %>%
  layer_flatten() %>%
  layer_dense(units = 16, activation = "relu") %>%
  layer_dense(units = 16, activation = "relu") %>%
  layer_dense(units = 1, activation = "sigmoid")


model1 %>% compile(
  #optimizer=optimizer_adam(),
  optimizer = "adam",
  loss = "binary_crossentropy",
  metrics = c("acc")
  )

summary(model1)
## Model: "sequential"
## _________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
##  Layer (type)                                         Output Shape                                    Param #            
## =========================================================================================================================
##  embedding (Embedding)                                (None, 300, 32)                                 1600000            
##  flatten (Flatten)                                    (None, 9600)                                    0                  
##  dense_2 (Dense)                                      (None, 16)                                      153616             
##  dense_1 (Dense)                                      (None, 16)                                      272                
##  dense (Dense)                                        (None, 1)                                       17                 
## =========================================================================================================================
## Total params: 1,753,905
## Trainable params: 1,753,905
## Non-trainable params: 0
## _________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
history <- model1 %>% fit(
  x_train, y_train,
  validation_data = list(x_val, y_val),
  epochs = 15, # 15 is probably enough
  batch_size = 128,
  verbose = 0
)

plot(history)

print(paste0("peak accuracy of the model: ",max(history$metrics$val_acc)))
## [1] "peak accuracy of the model: 0.75715833902359"

We can see that this model’s validation accuracy peaks at the 4th epoch, reaching 76.72%, which is already substantially better than the naive prediction which reached 50% validation accuracy. Overfitting sets in as early as the 2nd epoch, driving up validation loss. Validation accuracy however still increases slightly, indicating that while the model is overfitting to some degree, it continues learning useful features. The optimal model would therefore be trained for no more than 4 epochs on the given data.

rm(model1)
set_random_seed(32) 

model1 <- keras_model_sequential() %>%
  layer_embedding(input_dim = max_words, output_dim = 32,
                  input_length = maxlen) %>%
  layer_flatten() %>%
  layer_dense(units = 16, activation = "relu") %>%
  layer_dense(units = 16, activation = "relu") %>%
  layer_dense(units = 1, activation = "sigmoid")

model1 %>% compile(
  optimizer = "adam",
  loss = "binary_crossentropy",
  metrics = c("acc")
  )

model1 %>% fit(
  x_train, y_train,
  validation_data = list(x_val, y_val),
  epochs = 4,
  batch_size = 128,
  verbose = 0
)

Recurrent Neural Network (RNN)

The last model, a simple architecture using word embeddings and dense layers, already performed quite well. However, the history plot suggests that the model learns few new generalizable features (i.e. that improve validation performance) after the third epoch. We can try to improve the learning behavior by expanding the hypothesis space that the network can cover. One way to do this is by using recurrent neural network layers, which don’t just analyze individually words, but also consider their sequence. They’re thus able to “understand” meaning spread across multiple words, sentences, etc.

set_random_seed(32) 

model2 <- keras_model_sequential() %>%

LSTM Recurrent Layers

A more sophisticated approach to recurrent neural network layers are LSTM (Long-Short-Term-Memory) layers, which can dynamically update the model state to differently weigh information at greater and smaller distance from the current step (word) in the text sequence.

set_random_seed(32) 

model3 <- keras_model_sequential() %>%
  layer_embedding(input_dim = max_words, output_dim = 32,
                  input_length = maxlen) %>%
  layer_lstm(units = 32) %>%
  layer_dense(units = 1, activation = "sigmoid")


model3 %>% compile(
  optimizer = "adam",
  loss = "binary_crossentropy",
  metrics = c("acc")
  )

summary(model3)
## Model: "sequential_4"
## _________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
##  Layer (type)                                         Output Shape                                    Param #            
## =========================================================================================================================
##  embedding_4 (Embedding)                              (None, 300, 32)                                 1600000            
##  lstm (LSTM)                                          (None, 32)                                      8320               
##  dense_8 (Dense)                                      (None, 1)                                       33                 
## =========================================================================================================================
## Total params: 1,608,353
## Trainable params: 1,608,353
## Non-trainable params: 0
## _________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
history <- model3 %>% fit(
  x_train, y_train,
  validation_data = list(x_val, y_val),
  epochs = 25,
  batch_size = 128,
  verbose = 0
  )

plot(history)

print(paste0("peak accuracy of the model: ",max(history$metrics$val_acc)))
## [1] "peak accuracy of the model: 0.766268908977509"

This model keeps learning - albeit at a slow pace - and reaches an plateau around the 21st epoch with 77.33%.

We can further tweak the learning potential of the LSTM-based model by making the LSTM layer bi-directional. This way, the recurrent layer can parse information (e.g. relationships between words in a statement) both forwards and backwards, rather than only forwards.

set_random_seed(32) 

model3b <- keras_model_sequential() %>%
  layer_embedding(input_dim = max_words, output_dim = 32,
                  input_length = maxlen) %>%
  bidirectional(layer_lstm(units = 32)) %>%
  layer_dense(units = 1, activation = "sigmoid")


model3b %>% compile(
  optimizer = "adam",
  loss = "binary_crossentropy",
  metrics = c("acc")
  )

summary(model3b)

This model, still more computationally expensive, performs at about the same level as the uni-directional LSTM, plateauing from the 20th epoch on at an accuracy level around 77.49%.

1-Dimensional Convolutional Neural Network - checked

Another way to process sequential data (like text) is using 1-dimensional convolutional network layers, which are also able to learn multi-word/sentence patterns.

set_random_seed(32) 

model4 <- keras_model_sequential() %>%
  layer_embedding(input_dim = max_words, output_dim = 32,
                  input_length = maxlen) %>%
  layer_conv_1d(filters = 32, kernel_size = 7,
                activation = "relu") %>%
  layer_max_pooling_1d(pool_size = 5) %>%
  layer_conv_1d(filters = 32, kernel_size = 7,
                activation = "relu") %>%
  layer_global_max_pooling_1d() %>%
  layer_dense(units = 1, activation = "sigmoid")


model4 %>% compile(
  optimizer = "adam",
  loss = "binary_crossentropy",
  metrics = c("acc")
  )

Improving 1-Dimensional-Convolutional Neural Network

We may still improve the performance of this 1-D-Convolutional network, by expanding its hypothesis space. We can achieve this by adding embedding dimensions to the embeddings layer, and filters to the convolutional layers. Furthermore, adding batch normalization helps with training and regularizes the network to some degree.

set_random_seed(32) 

model5 <- keras_model_sequential() %>%
  layer_embedding(input_dim = max_words, output_dim = 64,
                  input_length = maxlen) %>%
  layer_conv_1d(filters = 64, kernel_size = 7,
                activation = "relu") %>%
  layer_batch_normalization() %>%
  layer_conv_1d(filters = 64, kernel_size = 7,
                activation = "relu") %>%
  layer_global_max_pooling_1d() %>%
  layer_batch_normalization() %>%
  layer_dense(units = 1, activation = "sigmoid")


model5 %>% compile(
  optimizer = "adam",
  loss = "binary_crossentropy",
  metrics = c("acc")
  )

summary(model5)

Aggregating predictions

After fitting the different models on individual paragraphs from the corporate reports, we can now aggregate the models’ predictions to the level of the whole reports, to arrive at a single scandal prediction for each of the companies .

aggregate_evaluate <- function(model){
  y_pred <- model %>% 
    predict(x_val) %>% as.numeric()
  y_pred <- y_pred %>%
    as.data.frame() %>%
    cbind(raw_test$company.x,raw_test$year,raw_test$ntoken)
  colnames(y_pred) <- c("y_pred","company","year","ntoken") 
  y_pred_firmyear <- y_pred %>%
    select(company,year,y_pred) %>%
    group_by(company,year) %>%
    summarise(scandal_prob = mean(y_pred))
  y_pred_firmyear$y_pred <- y_pred_firmyear$scandal_prob %>% 
  `>`(0.5) %>% k_cast("int32") %>% as.numeric()
  y_test_firmyear <- raw_test %>%
    mutate(label = as.numeric(future_controversy)) %>%
    select(company.x,year,label) %>%
    group_by(company.x,year) %>%
    summarise(label_firmyear = mean(label))
  confusion_mat <- confusionMatrix(factor(y_pred_firmyear$y_pred),
                                   factor(y_test_firmyear$label_firmyear))
  print(confusion_mat)
}
